{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe core deliverable of the epic: an `in_progress` ticket should carry the coding-agent\nsession that STARTED it, end-to-end (written on the STATUS event AND folded into compiled\nstate), additively — without disturbing `assignee` / `author`, and byte-identical to today\nwhen no session id is present. Recording without folding produces no observable outcome, so\nboth halves ship together.\n\n## What\n- **Write (`src/rebar/_commands/txn.py`).** In `claim_core` and `transition_core`, when the\n  event is an `open -> in_progress` STATUS, call the shared `resolve_session_id()` (story\n  6014) via a small `_stamp_session(status_data)` helper; when it returns non-None, add\n  `data[\"session\"]`. When None, OMIT the key entirely so the event bytes are identical to the\n  pre-feature path. Stamp on ANY `open -> in_progress` STATUS — the `claim` command AND a\n  bare `transition <id> open in_progress` (including the parent-first cascade) — not just\n  `claim`.\n- **Fold (`src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py`).** In `process_status`, a\n  `_fold_claimed_session(state, data)` helper sets `state[\"claimed_session\"] = data.get(\"session\")`\n  on the `open -> in_progress` edge (`current_status == \"open\" and status == \"in_progress\"`).\n  It is invoked ONLY in the two branches that APPLY this event's status — the normal-update\n  branch and the fork-WINNER branch — and NEVER in the branch where the existing chain wins,\n  so a losing concurrent claim never overwrites the winner's session (epic advisory G6/T8).\n  The edge condition reads the **incoming event's** `data.get(\"current_status\")` and\n  `data.get(\"status\")` — NOT the post-update `state[\"status\"]` (already mutated to\n  `in_progress` by the time the helper runs) — so in the fork-winner branch it still keys on\n  the event's declared `open -> in_progress` edge, never firing for a `<other> -> in_progress`\n  winner (advisory T8).\n  `claimed_session` records the session of the CURRENT claim episode (mirrors `assignee`): a\n  session-less re-claim folds `None`, deliberately CLEARING any stale prior id so the field\n  never mis-attributes the current in_progress slot to a past session (advisory T9). A later\n  non-claim edge (e.g. `blocked -> in_progress`) leaves it untouched.\n- **Initial-state default (`src/rebar/reducer/_state.py`).** Add `claimed_session: None` to\n  `make_initial_state()` (mirrors `assignee`), so a fresh event-replay always carries the key\n  (value `None`) rather than key-absent.\n- **Compiled-state schema (`src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json`).** Add a\n  `claimed_session: {type: [string, null]}` property beside `assignee` so the new public\n  compiled-state field is enumerated in the schema.\n- **Interim key-presence contract (until S3).** A snapshot persisted BEFORE this stack lacks\n  `claimed_session` entirely, so during the coexistence window a snapshot-served state may be\n  key-absent while a fresh-replay state is `None`. Consumers MUST therefore read via\n  `state.get(\"claimed_session\")` (tolerating both); S3 (199b) adds the snapshot-restore default\n  + compaction round-trip that closes the window. This story does not claim key-presence for\n  pre-existing snapshots.\n- **Forward/back-compat.** `data[\"session\"]` is an additive data key; a reducer build without\n  the fold ignores unknown data keys (it only reads `data.get(\"status\")` / `current_status`),\n  so an older clone tolerates the event. Absent-session events are byte-identical to today.\n- **Dependency.** The shared `resolve_session_id()` is story 6014, landed as the BASE COMMIT\n  of this stacked change series; this story is plan-reviewed with `--ref HEAD` so the review\n  snapshot includes it.\n\n## Scope\n- IN: the write stamp (both cores) + the reducer fold + the `make_initial_state` default +\n  the `ticket_state.schema.json` property + unit/integration tests (present,\n  absent/byte-identical, bare-transition, fork-winner gating, forward-compat tolerance,\n  session-less stale-clear, initial-state default).\n- OUT: snapshot/compaction default + pretty read surface + MCP outputSchema (S3 / 199b);\n  `OPENCODE_SESSION_ID`/`CODEX_THREAD_ID` + harness provenance (S5 / c557); capture hooks\n  (S4 / S6). The shared resolver itself is story 6014 (already landed as this stack's base).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Claiming with a session env var set records `claimed_session` in compiled state.\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k claim_records -q`.\n- [ ] Claiming with NO session env var set folds `claimed_session` to `None` (key-present,\n      consistent with the initial-state default) AND the written STATUS event carries no\n      `session` key (byte-identical no-session event path). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k absent -q` asserts\n      `state[\"claimed_session\"] is None` AND `\"session\" not in` the STATUS event's `data`.\n- [ ] A bare `transition <id> open in_progress` records it too (cascade parents included).\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k transition -q`.\n- [ ] Fork-winner gating: when two competing `open -> in_progress` STATUS events carry\n      DIFFERENT session ids, compiled `claimed_session` equals the lexical-UUID WINNER's\n      session (never the loser's). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k fork -q` replays both events in BOTH\n      orders and asserts the winner's session each time.\n- [ ] Forward-compat: `process_status` folds a STATUS whose `data` carries both `session` and\n      an arbitrary UNKNOWN extra key without error, and the unknown key does not enter state\n      (proxy for an older clone tolerating the additive key). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k forward_compat -q`.\n- [ ] Stale-clear (T9): a later `open -> in_progress` claim carrying NO session folds\n      `claimed_session` back to `None` (never leaves a stale prior id). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k session_less_reclaim -q`.\n- [ ] `make_initial_state()` defaults `claimed_session` to `None` (key-present). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k initial_state -q`.\n- [ ] `ticket_state.schema.json` enumerates `claimed_session` as `[string, null]`. Proof:\n      `grep -n '\"claimed_session\"' src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json`.\n\n## Depends on\n- S1 (shared resolver `resolve_session_id`) — landed as the base of this stack."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783541783204172001,"uuid":"55819cce-b6bc-4e0c-a53f-eb1a3982bfaa"}